<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-326-090  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 326 090.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  April 9 1990 v7 n15 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>German air traffic control service gets net overhaul.(network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Desmond, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bundesanstalt fur Flugsicherung (BFS), the Federal Administrationfor Air Navigation Services responsible for directing air trafficfor all flights in and out of West Germany, will undergo a $40million network upgrade that will replace a single Unisys 1183mainframe with three Unisys Series 2200 mainframes.andP;  Two of themainframes will be located at the primary data center, handlingdifferent applications and serving as hot backups for each other.andO;The third mainframe, located at a separate site and linked by afiber optic cable to the data center, will serve as backup for theentire system in case of a disaster at the primary site.andP;  BFS alsoplans to use Network Systems Corp's Hyperchannel to support thefiber optic link.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unisys Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    UIS.andO;Product:   Unisys 2200 (Mainframe computer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Back-Up SitesBack-Up SystemsAir Traffic ControlGermanyDisaster Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   West German air controllers plan for disaster. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>